oretical, its methodology is informed by the cognitive presuppositions of the social sciences, and its contents - dealing with the spiritual, personal, and social struggles that constitute daily life - are concrete. For Dumont religious truth is insufficient, and may have no impact on everyday life. What counts is relevance, insights that reply to urgent questions and unresolved conflicts. He offers an innovative interpretation of Catholicism that is faithful to the Gospel and relevant to the problems of modern life and the serious questions Quebecers are asking themselves. In Fernand Dumont: A Sociologist Turns to Theology, Baum elucidates Dumont’s main ideas and connects the concerns of the Christian gospel with those of contemporary society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristian sociology. 0aChristianismexPhilosophie. 0aChristianityxPhilosophy. 0aFaith. 0aPhilosophie et théologie. 0aSociologie religieusexChristianisme. 0aSociologistsxBiographyxQuébec (Province). 0aSociologistszQuébec (Province)vBiography. 0aSociologistszQuébec (Province)vBiography. 0aTheologianszQuébec (Province). 0aTheologians. 0aThéologiensxQuébec (Province)xQuébec. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Catholic.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311127402708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015z978311127703540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358245340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773582453423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773582453/original  a978-3-11-127402-7  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  a978-3-11-127703-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles